It's what you have
to nail in order

00:02:40.210 --> 00:02:45.580
to deliver long-term,
highly satisfied users.

00:02:45.580 --> 00:02:47.530
As Dave said in the
keynote this morning,

00:02:47.530 --> 00:02:49.720
Android TV has seen
tremendous growth.

00:02:49.720 --> 00:02:52.870
I think his stats were a million
new activations every two

00:02:52.870 --> 00:02:53.960
months.

00:02:53.960 --> 00:02:57.760
But as they say, the
best is yet to come.

00:02:57.760 --> 00:03:00.400
So we launched Android
TV three years ago,

00:03:00.400 --> 00:03:02.890
and since then
we've learned a lot.

00:03:02.890 --> 00:03:04.540
But this year we
took the opportunity

00:03:04.540 --> 00:03:06.730
to take a step
back and take stock

00:03:06.730 --> 00:03:09.520
of where we were on
the platform, and also

00:03:09.520 --> 00:03:10.950
how changes--

00:03:10.950 --> 00:03:14.200
to how people were engaging with
content in the living rooms.

00:03:14.200 --> 00:03:16.210
Now across the
industry, we found

00:03:16.210 --> 00:03:19.120
these three common issues,
these three core needs that

00:03:19.120 --> 00:03:21.340
were really going unaddressed.

00:03:21.340 --> 00:03:23.980
So the first thing we saw
was that it's really hard

00:03:23.980 --> 00:03:26.290
to come to grips with
all the different content

00:03:26.290 --> 00:03:27.530
available to us.

00:03:27.530 --> 00:03:29.290
So families now have
multiple sources

00:03:29.290 --> 00:03:31.870
for what they want to watch
depending on the mood,

00:03:31.870 --> 00:03:33.550
the time of day,
who's in the room,

00:03:33.550 --> 00:03:35.050
and a bunch of other factors.

00:03:35.050 --> 00:03:36.550
And it's interesting
because content

00:03:36.550 --> 00:03:40.370
is mostly visible within
the app or service.

00:03:40.370 --> 00:03:42.460
So what you do is
you turn on the TV,

00:03:42.460 --> 00:03:45.640
and you have to actually
like deep dive into the app

00:03:45.640 --> 00:03:48.010
to see if it has
something you're actually

00:03:48.010 --> 00:03:49.780
interested in watching.

00:03:49.780 --> 00:03:52.900
So it's become really hard
to know what's available

00:03:52.900 --> 00:03:55.180
before you figure out who
you want to watch it from,

00:03:55.180 --> 00:03:58.810
which we kind of realize is
a bit of a weird situation.

00:03:58.810 --> 00:04:00.340
Also, the problem
gets a bit harder

00:04:00.340 --> 00:04:02.560
because there are so many
different types of content

00:04:02.560 --> 00:04:04.000
available to watch.

00:04:04.000 --> 00:04:05.650
Could be video on
demand, and that

00:04:05.650 --> 00:04:09.400
could be through a
subscription, paid or rented.

00:04:09.400 --> 00:04:13.450
It could be digital, web-driven
sort of social content.

00:04:13.450 --> 00:04:16.420
Or it could be live
television through a pay TV

00:04:16.420 --> 00:04:20.170
subscription or an antenna
or over the air source.

00:04:20.170 --> 00:04:22.089
So as of yet, it's
been really hard

00:04:22.089 --> 00:04:24.580
to fold all of these
different types of content

00:04:24.580 --> 00:04:28.550
into an empowering
experience for users.

00:04:28.550 --> 00:04:31.240
So the second thing we saw
is that the emotional hook

00:04:31.240 --> 00:04:34.720
from a piece of content that
we see, it's diminishing.

00:04:34.720 --> 00:04:36.700
You can imagine that
we may have found

00:04:36.700 --> 00:04:38.550
our way into a list of options.

00:04:38.550 --> 00:04:40.820
It could be recommendations
or something like that.

00:04:40.820 --> 00:04:43.960
And we're seeing the movie art
or poster art and we're just,

00:04:43.960 --> 00:04:45.970
we're not feeling
connected to any of it.

00:04:45.970 --> 00:04:47.740
Now with this huge
number of options

00:04:47.740 --> 00:04:50.890
for content available
to us, which we love,

00:04:50.890 --> 00:04:53.830
we like a big menu, but
we're losing our ability

00:04:53.830 --> 00:04:55.690
to make a decision.

00:04:55.690 --> 00:04:57.640
Now we saw users
with these huge lists

00:04:57.640 --> 00:04:58.920
of options available to them.

00:04:58.920 --> 00:05:01.420
Maybe there's a watch
list that they've curated,

00:05:01.420 --> 00:05:04.420
or maybe there's recommendations
that they've made sure,

00:05:04.420 --> 00:05:06.580
you know, as much as
possible that it reflects

00:05:06.580 --> 00:05:07.930
what they want to watch.

00:05:07.930 --> 00:05:10.600
But when the time comes to
actually play something off

00:05:10.600 --> 00:05:12.662
of that, they really
can't find the spark

00:05:12.662 --> 00:05:14.620
that they originally had,
why they put it there

00:05:14.620 --> 00:05:15.950
in the first place.

00:05:15.950 --> 00:05:18.130
So the watch list
had become more

00:05:18.130 --> 00:05:21.910
aspirational than actionable.

00:05:21.910 --> 00:05:25.000
The third thing we saw, people
were really looking for ways

00:05:25.000 --> 00:05:28.120
to tweak the content on
a device to customize it

00:05:28.120 --> 00:05:29.830
for how they want to watch.

00:05:29.830 --> 00:05:31.450
So when you bring
a TV into your home

00:05:31.450 --> 00:05:36.147
and you sign up for a service or
an app, the shows, the actors,

00:05:36.147 --> 00:05:37.480
they become part of your family.

00:05:37.480 --> 00:05:38.380
They're part of your routine.

00:05:38.380 --> 00:05:39.600
You watch them every night.

00:05:39.600 --> 00:05:41.650
It's like a ritual.

00:05:41.650 --> 00:05:44.230
We think that part of this
should be being able to nest

00:05:44.230 --> 00:05:47.290
with the device, to customize
the experience so that it fits

00:05:47.290 --> 00:05:50.330
with your life and your needs.

00:05:50.330 --> 00:05:53.860
If you watch people get
a new TV or a new phone,

00:05:53.860 --> 00:05:56.440
one of the first things they
do is they sort of move things

00:05:56.440 --> 00:05:57.130
around, right?

00:05:57.130 --> 00:05:58.420
You move the apps around.

00:05:58.420 --> 00:05:59.440
You set the background.

00:05:59.440 --> 00:06:00.610
You set your ring tone.

00:06:00.610 --> 00:06:04.480
You customize it to how
you want to use the device.

00:06:04.480 --> 00:06:07.720
But with TV, from a
content perspective,

00:06:07.720 --> 00:06:10.750
people really can't do that.

00:06:10.750 --> 00:06:12.967
Now these concerns have
been around for some time.

00:06:12.967 --> 00:06:14.050
We're not surfacing these.

00:06:14.050 --> 00:06:16.240
These are the only people
to have ever discovered

00:06:16.240 --> 00:06:17.170
these things.

00:06:17.170 --> 00:06:21.220
But they come out now and again
in user research and market

00:06:21.220 --> 00:06:22.530
and analyst reports.

00:06:22.530 --> 00:06:24.160
They're known issues.

00:06:24.160 --> 00:06:27.340
But what we've done is we've
taken these issues to heart

00:06:27.340 --> 00:06:30.700
in Android O, and we've set
out to directly address them

00:06:30.700 --> 00:06:34.690
with a major refresh
of Android TV.

00:06:34.690 --> 00:06:36.700
Now the first major
change you probably

00:06:36.700 --> 00:06:38.076
have already heard about.

00:06:38.076 --> 00:06:40.450
Earlier this year, we announced
that the Google Assistant

00:06:40.450 --> 00:06:42.490
will be coming to Android TV.

00:06:42.490 --> 00:06:44.950
The Google Assistant is
your own personal Google.

00:06:44.950 --> 00:06:46.250
You can ask it questions.

00:06:46.250 --> 00:06:47.692
You can tell it to do things.

00:06:47.692 --> 00:06:49.150
It's always ready
to help, and it's

00:06:49.150 --> 00:06:50.810
available across
all of your devices,

00:06:50.810 --> 00:06:52.850
so you can integrate
it into your life.

00:06:52.850 --> 00:06:56.200
Now what does that
really mean for TV?

00:06:56.200 --> 00:06:58.600
Well, one of the core
design principles

00:06:58.600 --> 00:07:00.730
in bringing the
assistant to the TV

00:07:00.730 --> 00:07:03.110
was that people are
trained from a young age

00:07:03.110 --> 00:07:05.710
to talk about media
with others, to use

00:07:05.710 --> 00:07:08.950
our voice in the discussion
about what we want to watch

00:07:08.950 --> 00:07:10.000
or what we feel.

00:07:10.000 --> 00:07:12.490
I do this frequently
with friends and family.

00:07:12.490 --> 00:07:15.250
We go back and forth about what
we're interested in, figure out

00:07:15.250 --> 00:07:18.550
if it's a show or a movie,
how much time we have left,

00:07:18.550 --> 00:07:22.240
what's available to us, and
we arrive at a decision.

00:07:22.240 --> 00:07:24.241
This sort of interaction
feels very natural.

00:07:24.241 --> 00:07:25.990
It's what we're used
to when we're dealing

00:07:25.990 --> 00:07:28.340
with people in everyday life.

00:07:28.340 --> 00:07:31.810
Now we think that voice is an
amazing augmentation for media

00:07:31.810 --> 00:07:34.700
consumption in the living room.

00:07:34.700 --> 00:07:37.990
So what we've done is we've
optimized the assistant on TV

00:07:37.990 --> 00:07:40.390
from the ground up
to fill this role.

00:07:40.390 --> 00:07:43.510
That means with an Android TV,
you can use the remote alone

00:07:43.510 --> 00:07:44.980
to navigate the UI.

00:07:44.980 --> 00:07:46.810
You can use the voice
button on the remote

00:07:46.810 --> 00:07:48.880
and you'll be able to
talk to the assistant.

00:07:48.880 --> 00:07:51.580
Or you can use the assistant
in a hands-free mode

00:07:51.580 --> 00:07:54.160
to discover and play content.

00:07:54.160 --> 00:07:57.530
Even better, you can transition
between these modes seamlessly.

00:07:57.530 --> 00:08:01.360
So whatever you want to do, it
fits the situation you're in.

00:08:01.360 --> 00:08:03.940
If you want to talk, it's there.

00:08:03.940 --> 00:08:06.820
If not, no big deal.

00:08:06.820 --> 00:08:09.430
Now there was a bunch of work
that went into us getting here.

00:08:09.430 --> 00:08:12.250
We had to build multiple
speech models, UI that's

00:08:12.250 --> 00:08:14.700
responsive to the situation
and context of a user,

00:08:14.700 --> 00:08:16.490
and a number of other things.

00:08:16.490 --> 00:08:19.270
But what it's resulted in
is a new, more natural,

00:08:19.270 --> 00:08:22.150
and transparent way of
interacting with your TV.

00:08:22.150 --> 00:08:24.250
In addition, because it's
the same assistant that

00:08:24.250 --> 00:08:27.136
connects your Google and third
party services and devices,

00:08:27.136 --> 00:08:29.260
you can use it in a bunch
of interesting scenarios.

00:08:29.260 --> 00:08:31.930
So actually, let's take
a look at one of these.

00:08:31.930 --> 00:08:35.280
Let's imagine it's Friday night
and I'd like to watch a movie.

00:08:35.280 --> 00:08:39.010
I might say, show me some
recent action movies.

00:08:39.010 --> 00:08:41.289
Now the Google
Assistant knows it's me,

00:08:41.289 --> 00:08:43.150
and it knows the
context, where I'm

00:08:43.150 --> 00:08:46.000
at, and what sorts of things
I'm interested in, like actors,

00:08:46.000 --> 00:08:47.107
for example.

00:08:47.107 --> 00:08:49.690
So it's going to bring up a list
of things that might interest

00:08:49.690 --> 00:08:52.209
me from multiple sources.

00:08:52.209 --> 00:08:54.250
There might be a way to
further refine the search

00:08:54.250 --> 00:08:56.260
or broaden it, but
let's assume for now

00:08:56.260 --> 00:08:58.279
that I see what I'm looking for.

00:08:58.279 --> 00:09:00.070
One thing to note is
that the assistant can

00:09:00.070 --> 00:09:02.081
work in a conversational
manner, meaning

00:09:02.081 --> 00:09:04.330
that it's going to remember
the context I have in case

00:09:04.330 --> 00:09:05.496
there's a follow up request.

00:09:05.496 --> 00:09:08.060
So I think I see something
I'm interested this.

00:09:08.060 --> 00:09:11.170
In this case, I want to watch
Deadpool, which is a hilarious

00:09:11.170 --> 00:09:12.560
movie, by the way.

00:09:12.560 --> 00:09:15.280
But if, for example,
it's a complicated title,

00:09:15.280 --> 00:09:18.310
or if I'm feeling a
bit lazy, I might just

00:09:18.310 --> 00:09:21.604
refer to it by the
order it is in the list,

00:09:21.604 --> 00:09:23.770
like I might be talking to
someone else in the room.

00:09:23.770 --> 00:09:26.932
So I might say,
play the third one.

00:09:26.932 --> 00:09:29.140
Now what's happened is that
the assistant understands

00:09:29.140 --> 00:09:30.670
where we're at in
the conversation

00:09:30.670 --> 00:09:31.753
and what I'm trying to do.

00:09:31.753 --> 00:09:34.270
And so it's going to play
the content that I requested

00:09:34.270 --> 00:09:36.700
from the source that I had.

00:09:36.700 --> 00:09:38.320
And maybe the movie
is just starting

00:09:38.320 --> 00:09:40.450
and the family is sitting
down ready to watch,

00:09:40.450 --> 00:09:43.030
and we realize we want to make
the experience a little bit

00:09:43.030 --> 00:09:43.840
more comfortable.

00:09:43.840 --> 00:09:47.290
So because it's
the assistant, it's

00:09:47.290 --> 00:09:49.070
connected to the other
devices in my house

00:09:49.070 --> 00:09:51.070
and I can control the
lighting in my living room

00:09:51.070 --> 00:09:52.300
just by asking.

00:09:52.300 --> 00:09:55.390
So I might say, dim the lights.

00:09:55.390 --> 00:09:59.890
And the lights dim, and we're
ready to watch the movie.

00:09:59.890 --> 00:10:01.720
Now the second major change.

00:10:01.720 --> 00:10:04.000
They say home is
where the heart is.

00:10:04.000 --> 00:10:08.230
So in order to truly change
the way people use Android TV,

00:10:08.230 --> 00:10:11.980
we had to make a
change to our home.

00:10:11.980 --> 00:10:15.700
For Android O, we've redefined
the home screen on Android TV

00:10:15.700 --> 00:10:19.960
to be a channel-based,
content first experience.

00:10:19.960 --> 00:10:22.190
This new home enables
users to engage

00:10:22.190 --> 00:10:23.770
with the content
and apps that they

00:10:23.770 --> 00:10:26.460
love all in the same place.

00:10:26.460 --> 00:10:29.000
Now instead of showing you
more screen shots up here,

00:10:29.000 --> 00:10:29.930
we decided--

00:10:29.930 --> 00:10:31.430
at a bit of risk to ourself--

00:10:31.430 --> 00:10:34.414
to actually give you a live
demo using a developer device

00:10:34.414 --> 00:10:36.830
that we have, and we'll walk
through the features on that.

00:10:36.830 --> 00:10:38.830
So could we switch to the
next displayer please?

00:10:42.157 --> 00:10:43.740
Isaac's going to
help me out for this.

00:10:43.740 --> 00:10:45.469
So I wanted to call
out that we're still

00:10:45.469 --> 00:10:47.510
putting the finishing
touches on this experience.

00:10:47.510 --> 00:10:51.200
So you should expect to
see further visual changes

00:10:51.200 --> 00:10:53.990
and performance improvements
as we move closer to launch.

