00:22:06.769 --> 00:22:08.560
ISAAC KATZENELSON: So
let's talk specifics.

00:22:08.560 --> 00:22:10.810
What can you, the
app developer, do

00:22:10.810 --> 00:22:14.950
to showcase your content, your
app content on the Home screen?

00:22:14.950 --> 00:22:16.130
We start with the basics.

00:22:16.130 --> 00:22:19.730
We're using two well-known
Android concepts.

00:22:19.730 --> 00:22:21.940
The first one is the
content provider.

00:22:21.940 --> 00:22:24.160
We use content
providers with new APIs

00:22:24.160 --> 00:22:26.650
for storing channel
and programs data.

00:22:26.650 --> 00:22:29.350
Your app should insert
channel and program data

00:22:29.350 --> 00:22:31.390
into the providers
and the system

00:22:31.390 --> 00:22:34.290
will automatically show it.

00:22:34.290 --> 00:22:36.220
The other concept is
we're using intent

00:22:36.220 --> 00:22:39.050
to tell your app when to
insert your first channel

00:22:39.050 --> 00:22:42.730
and when your user is
interacting with your content.

00:22:42.730 --> 00:22:44.440
You will use a
broadcast receiver

00:22:44.440 --> 00:22:47.620
to listen to this intent
and act upon them.

00:22:47.620 --> 00:22:49.790
And of course, to
make it easier,

00:22:49.790 --> 00:22:53.410
we provide the support library
for easier implementation.

00:22:53.410 --> 00:22:55.820
But what exactly
do you need to do?

00:22:55.820 --> 00:22:59.710
What should the app
do and exactly when?

00:22:59.710 --> 00:23:04.060
So to better understand it, I'm
introducing Chez Isaac, a brand

00:23:04.060 --> 00:23:09.160
new fictional Android TV app.

00:23:09.160 --> 00:23:11.620
The app allows users
to watch cooking videos

00:23:11.620 --> 00:23:14.710
in different categories,
favorite them, rate them,

00:23:14.710 --> 00:23:16.800
and create personal
content channels.

00:23:16.800 --> 00:23:19.810
And I will show you what I
did in my app to showcase

00:23:19.810 --> 00:23:22.400
my content on the Home screen.

00:23:22.400 --> 00:23:23.775
So let's begin.

00:23:23.775 --> 00:23:25.150
The first thing
I added to my app

00:23:25.150 --> 00:23:27.430
is a broadcast receiver
to listen to this intent,

00:23:27.430 --> 00:23:29.145
the initialize_programs intent.

00:23:29.145 --> 00:23:32.360
The intent is sent to
your app, to my app

00:23:32.360 --> 00:23:35.540
once the app is installed.

00:23:35.540 --> 00:23:39.070
So very basically,
broadcast receiver,

00:23:39.070 --> 00:23:42.550
they listen to
initialize_program intent.

00:23:42.550 --> 00:23:45.190
Once the receiver is
called, I start a job.

00:23:45.190 --> 00:23:48.500
I use a job scheduler-- or you
can use Firebase Job Dispatcher

00:23:48.500 --> 00:23:49.870
too, it doesn't really matter--

00:23:49.870 --> 00:23:51.901
and I insert my channels.

00:23:51.901 --> 00:23:54.400
So I decided to insert three
channels, two or three channels

00:23:54.400 --> 00:23:56.890
is about the right
number of channels,

00:23:56.890 --> 00:24:02.870
I can finetune it later when
I know my users tastes better.

00:24:02.870 --> 00:24:05.390
So as you can see,
I schedule using

00:24:05.390 --> 00:24:07.340
a job scheduler and a task.

00:24:07.340 --> 00:24:11.240
If you notice the 0 on the
setMinimumLatency, when

00:24:11.240 --> 00:24:13.590
you set it to 0, it means
that the system will actually

00:24:13.590 --> 00:24:15.470
schedule this job
immediately, which

00:24:15.470 --> 00:24:18.230
is a good thing because we
need the channel to be visible

00:24:18.230 --> 00:24:21.500
immediately after
the app is installed.

00:24:21.500 --> 00:24:24.230
The job runs a simple task
that actually pulls data

00:24:24.230 --> 00:24:27.350
off my channels from my
back end and insert them

00:24:27.350 --> 00:24:29.932
into the provider.

00:24:29.932 --> 00:24:30.890
But how do you do that?

00:24:30.890 --> 00:24:33.470
So how do you
insert the channel?

00:24:33.470 --> 00:24:35.620
So we have, in the
support library,

00:24:35.620 --> 00:24:37.280
is several builders
to help you build

00:24:37.280 --> 00:24:40.770
channels and programs to
insert them into the provider.

00:24:40.770 --> 00:24:43.520
So I use the support
library channel builder

00:24:43.520 --> 00:24:45.140
to create a channel,
and you can see,

00:24:45.140 --> 00:24:47.360
I set up that type to preview.

00:24:47.360 --> 00:24:50.240
I set the display name
to the channel name.

00:24:50.240 --> 00:24:53.340
And I set a link back
to my app, so when

00:24:53.340 --> 00:24:56.990
the user clicks on the channel
icon, it actually opens my app.

00:24:56.990 --> 00:25:00.440
And I use a ContentResolver
to call insert and just insert

00:25:00.440 --> 00:25:03.350
the data into the provider.

00:25:03.350 --> 00:25:05.420
And the last thing to do
is actually add a logo

00:25:05.420 --> 00:25:06.500
to my channel.

00:25:06.500 --> 00:25:09.140
So there's a call for that,
and actually, you can either

00:25:09.140 --> 00:25:11.680
provide a bitmap,
or if it's too hard,

00:25:11.680 --> 00:25:13.700
then you can provide
a URL to the bitmap

00:25:13.700 --> 00:25:16.210
somewhere on the internet
and the support app.

00:25:16.210 --> 00:25:20.980
It will download it for you
and actually insert it for you.

00:25:20.980 --> 00:25:22.200
Same thing for programs.

00:25:22.200 --> 00:25:27.090
For each channel, I will use a
builder to insert the programs.

00:25:27.090 --> 00:25:29.370
So I set the channel
ID, the same one

00:25:29.370 --> 00:25:32.730
that I created before, I
set the type from each clip,

00:25:32.730 --> 00:25:34.250
I set the title,
the description,

00:25:34.250 --> 00:25:36.590
there's way more
metadata to insert,

00:25:36.590 --> 00:25:38.680
I'll talk about
this a bit later.

00:25:38.680 --> 00:25:41.284
And then I insert the URI that
will actually when clicking,

00:25:41.284 --> 00:25:42.200
will play the content.

00:25:42.200 --> 00:25:44.550
Will call my app to
play the content.

00:25:44.550 --> 00:25:46.590
And again, I use
the ContentResolver

00:25:46.590 --> 00:25:49.980
to insert it into the provider.

00:25:49.980 --> 00:25:52.050
And the last thing I need
to do is ask the system

00:25:52.050 --> 00:25:54.060
to make the channel visible.

00:25:54.060 --> 00:25:56.520
And to do that, I
do one simple call,

00:25:56.520 --> 00:26:01.500
I request it to be visible,
browsable, and presto!

00:26:01.500 --> 00:26:02.070
That's it.

00:26:02.070 --> 00:26:04.980
I created my first channel.

00:26:04.980 --> 00:26:08.000
I want to take a moment to
talk about the first channel.

00:26:08.000 --> 00:26:09.540
When the app is
installed, it gets

00:26:09.540 --> 00:26:11.640
what we called a golden ticket.

00:26:11.640 --> 00:26:13.080
The ticket, which
the app can use

00:26:13.080 --> 00:26:15.630
to insert the channel
without the user approving.

00:26:15.630 --> 00:26:19.620
It will be visible by default.
The app gets a one golden

00:26:19.620 --> 00:26:21.600
ticket, so once you
insert the first channel,

00:26:21.600 --> 00:26:25.030
this ticket is gone and
cannot be used anymore.

00:26:25.030 --> 00:26:26.820
So if you want to add
additional channels,

00:26:26.820 --> 00:26:29.200
it needs to be
approved by the user.

00:26:29.200 --> 00:26:30.810
So the first thing
you need to do

00:26:30.810 --> 00:26:34.410
is do not remove your first
channel, your default channel.

00:26:34.410 --> 00:26:37.960
Use it, update it,
but don't remove it.

00:26:37.960 --> 00:26:40.030
Since my app shows
video clip, I will use

00:26:40.030 --> 00:26:41.980
the program type called Clip.

00:26:41.980 --> 00:26:44.350
But there are many other
program types to use

00:26:44.350 --> 00:26:46.300
and it depends on
the content that you

00:26:46.300 --> 00:26:49.090
showing what types to use.

00:26:49.090 --> 00:26:52.510
And each type has a different
metadata associated with it.

00:26:52.510 --> 00:26:55.090
The API documentation's
All line show

00:26:55.090 --> 00:26:57.430
very well what
exactly the metadata

00:26:57.430 --> 00:27:01.880
you need for each clip
type, for each program type.

00:27:01.880 --> 00:27:06.890
So just to show, we have
seven type of video programs,

00:27:06.890 --> 00:27:10.490
from movies to TV season
and life channels.

00:27:10.490 --> 00:27:12.950
And you can understand
that if I use a TV episode,

00:27:12.950 --> 00:27:16.710
I may have that episode
number and the season number,

00:27:16.710 --> 00:27:18.442
which will not be
relevant to a movie,

00:27:18.442 --> 00:27:20.650
so it will use different
metadata for different kinds

00:27:20.650 --> 00:27:21.956
of programs.

00:27:21.956 --> 00:27:23.330
The same thing
for audio, we have

00:27:23.330 --> 00:27:26.750
five types of audio programs.

00:27:26.750 --> 00:27:31.490
Talking about metadata,
each app has a title.

00:27:31.490 --> 00:27:34.290
It has a description.

00:27:34.290 --> 00:27:37.460
It has more metadata,
like the release date,

00:27:37.460 --> 00:27:40.790
the length of the program, the
user rating, there's author,

00:27:40.790 --> 00:27:44.840
there is price, there's
many more fields available.

00:27:44.840 --> 00:27:47.160
And of course, for
the visual part of it,

00:27:47.160 --> 00:27:48.740
which is the most
important part,

00:27:48.740 --> 00:27:53.720
you can insert two
different images.

00:27:53.720 --> 00:27:56.470
One is when the actually
image is focused,

00:27:56.470 --> 00:27:59.750
your program is focused
on the Home UI and one,

00:27:59.750 --> 00:28:00.980
when it's not focused.

00:28:00.980 --> 00:28:03.440
And of course, you can also
use the preview video, which

00:28:03.440 --> 00:28:05.430
has the most visual effect.

00:28:05.430 --> 00:28:07.040
The more metadata
you add, the better.

00:28:12.220 --> 00:28:15.240
So my app is installed
on the device,

00:28:15.240 --> 00:28:17.590
the user used it,
watched a few videos,

00:28:17.590 --> 00:28:22.110
even added a second channel
using the customize channel

00:28:22.110 --> 00:28:23.156
and it's great.

00:28:23.156 --> 00:28:24.780
But I want the user
to be engaged more,

00:28:24.780 --> 00:28:27.750
I want the user to go back to
my app and watch more content.

00:28:27.750 --> 00:28:29.490
So how do I do that?

00:28:29.490 --> 00:28:32.220
To do that, I need to
keep my content fresh,

00:28:32.220 --> 00:28:34.690
to update my channels
all the time.

00:28:34.690 --> 00:28:36.870
So what I did, I
used Cloud Messaging

00:28:36.870 --> 00:28:39.000
to have my back end
ping back to my app

00:28:39.000 --> 00:28:41.100
when new content is available.

00:28:41.100 --> 00:28:45.150
When my app gets this ping, this
message, I run a job-- again,

00:28:45.150 --> 00:28:48.240
I run a job in the background
to put this new content

00:28:48.240 --> 00:28:52.240
from my back end server, and
also, to query the data that's

00:28:52.240 --> 00:28:56.160
actually on the device in the
provider, so I know what's new

00:28:56.160 --> 00:28:57.690
and what's already
on the device.

00:28:57.690 --> 00:29:03.120
And I'm going to sync, kind of
consolidate the two data sets.

00:29:03.120 --> 00:29:06.540
When I do that, I try to do
what I call a smart sync.

00:29:06.540 --> 00:29:08.800
So I will compare
the two data sets

00:29:08.800 --> 00:29:11.550
and then I will remove all
programs that are not available

00:29:11.550 --> 00:29:14.340
anymore, I will add
new ones that are new,

00:29:14.340 --> 00:29:16.870
and the ones that are still
there, I can update them.

00:29:16.870 --> 00:29:19.650
Maybe the release date changed,
maybe the number of views

00:29:19.650 --> 00:29:22.020
changed, I can do that,
update the programs

00:29:22.020 --> 00:29:24.660
and also maybe change the
order, because some of them

00:29:24.660 --> 00:29:28.830
are more popular than
others and that's OK.

00:29:28.830 --> 00:29:33.630
We try to avoid the
remove all/add all concept

00:29:33.630 --> 00:29:35.790
or paradigm, because
what happens,

00:29:35.790 --> 00:29:40.600
if you do the smart sync,
the visual will be better.

00:29:40.600 --> 00:29:43.080
There'll be less visual
glitches, little glitches,

00:29:43.080 --> 00:29:48.670
movements on your channel, and
that's what we're aiming for.

00:29:48.670 --> 00:29:52.080
So I have more channels, I
have them with fresh new data--

00:29:52.080 --> 00:29:54.390
what's next?

00:29:54.390 --> 00:29:57.240
So I added a feature into
my app to actually allow

00:29:57.240 --> 00:30:00.330
the user to add channels
from the app itself.

00:30:00.330 --> 00:30:03.120
So when the user is interested
in a topic or a category,

00:30:03.120 --> 00:30:06.840
I pop up a view
which has a button

00:30:06.840 --> 00:30:11.250
to suggest the user to add the
channel to the Home screen.

00:30:11.250 --> 00:30:13.980
When the user clicks on
it, what I need to do

00:30:13.980 --> 00:30:15.070
is a few simple things.

00:30:15.070 --> 00:30:17.444
First of all, again, I need
to build a channel to insert,

00:30:17.444 --> 00:30:19.200
so I use the Program
Builder to insert

00:30:19.200 --> 00:30:24.120
the channels and the
programs into the provider,

00:30:24.120 --> 00:30:26.910
and then I do one more
thing is ask the system

00:30:26.910 --> 00:30:28.500
to make it visible.

00:30:28.500 --> 00:30:31.080
And the way it works
is that I create

00:30:31.080 --> 00:30:33.270
an intent, which is
called channel_browsable,

00:30:33.270 --> 00:30:37.180
request channel_browsable, then
I do startActivity for example.

00:30:37.180 --> 00:30:40.350
This tells the system to
actually show a confirmation

00:30:40.350 --> 00:30:41.400
screen.

00:30:41.400 --> 00:30:43.980
And remember, the
golden ticket is gone,

00:30:43.980 --> 00:30:46.830
you need the user approval,
the user can approve or not.

00:30:46.830 --> 00:30:48.820
And when they user
approves it or not,

00:30:48.820 --> 00:30:51.570
what it actually know
what the user replied

00:30:51.570 --> 00:30:53.352
by checking on
activity result. And I

00:30:53.352 --> 00:30:55.060
know if the user
actually approved or not

00:30:55.060 --> 00:30:58.331
and do with it what I want.

00:30:58.331 --> 00:30:58.830
Woohoo!

00:30:58.830 --> 00:31:00.700
Three channels now
on the Home screen.

00:31:00.700 --> 00:31:01.720
Good job!

00:31:01.720 --> 00:31:03.260
So lets move on.

00:31:03.260 --> 00:31:05.320
So another opportunity
to engage the user

00:31:05.320 --> 00:31:06.960
is actually the
Watch Next channel.

00:31:06.960 --> 00:31:09.820
Remember that was the channel
that was on top of the screen,

00:31:09.820 --> 00:31:12.280
and it's a system channel, so
you don't have to create it,

00:31:12.280 --> 00:31:17.480
but you do need to follow some
guidelines in order to use it.

00:31:17.480 --> 00:31:19.330
So the first thing I
did, I added support

00:31:19.330 --> 00:31:22.850
in my app to actually monitor
what's added to the Watch Next

00:31:22.850 --> 00:31:23.350
channels.

00:31:23.350 --> 00:31:26.080
Every time a program is added
to the Watch Next channels that

00:31:26.080 --> 00:31:27.970
is my program, I
want to know about it

00:31:27.970 --> 00:31:29.440
and I want to track this.

00:31:29.440 --> 00:31:31.180
So it's a very simple API.

00:31:31.180 --> 00:31:35.380
You can add, remove, and
check if the program is

00:31:35.380 --> 00:31:36.940
in the Watch Next channel.

00:31:36.940 --> 00:31:41.590
And you can implement it with
a database or shared prefs--

00:31:41.590 --> 00:31:44.330
pretty easy thing to do.

00:31:44.330 --> 00:31:46.640
So let's look at some use cases.

00:31:46.640 --> 00:31:48.560
So let's talk about
the Continue Playing.

00:31:48.560 --> 00:31:50.670
So the user watch
one of my videos,

00:31:50.670 --> 00:31:52.600
but didn't finish watching it.

00:31:52.600 --> 00:31:54.430
So what do I do?

00:31:54.430 --> 00:31:57.550
What I need to do is actually
add a program, like before,

00:31:57.550 --> 00:31:58.840
the same concept.

00:31:58.840 --> 00:32:01.140
I set that type,
the clip, I edit

00:32:01.140 --> 00:32:03.680
another type, which
is what kind of type

00:32:03.680 --> 00:32:05.074
is on the Watch Next channel?

00:32:05.074 --> 00:32:06.490
This time, it's
Continue Watching,

00:32:06.490 --> 00:32:08.650
what we call Continue Here.

00:32:08.650 --> 00:32:10.580
And then I add three
more data to it.

00:32:10.580 --> 00:32:12.450
One is, when did it happen?

00:32:12.450 --> 00:32:14.500
And the other two to
help us with the UI

00:32:14.500 --> 00:32:17.500
is, two, the length
of the program

00:32:17.500 --> 00:32:20.140
and the current play position.

00:32:20.140 --> 00:32:23.170
And again, simply again just
insert it into the provider

00:32:23.170 --> 00:32:23.965
and you're done.

00:32:23.965 --> 00:32:25.840
And if there's a Keep
on Playing the Content,

00:32:25.840 --> 00:32:30.620
I can just update the current
play position to update the UI.

00:32:30.620 --> 00:32:31.120
Great.

00:32:31.120 --> 00:32:33.940
I have another card in
the Watch Next channel.

00:32:33.940 --> 00:32:36.610
One more thing I can do is
that if I have some clips that

00:32:36.610 --> 00:32:39.190
are part of a
season or a series,

00:32:39.190 --> 00:32:41.890
when the user, say,
is watching episode 2,

00:32:41.890 --> 00:32:45.280
I can insert episode 3 and say,
that's the next one to watch.

00:32:45.280 --> 00:32:47.550
Or maybe if at the
end of the season

00:32:47.550 --> 00:32:52.070
and into the next season, I can
add a card for the next season.

00:32:52.070 --> 00:32:57.610
So what I did is actually edit,
again, a program by same type,

00:32:57.610 --> 00:32:58.890
clip--

00:32:58.890 --> 00:33:00.550
Watch Next is next.

00:33:00.550 --> 00:33:03.160
At the top is next,
like next item.

00:33:03.160 --> 00:33:06.340
And just adding when
I inserted it in so

00:33:06.340 --> 00:33:07.440
it will be in the system.

00:33:12.020 --> 00:33:16.440
And again, I have another card
on the Watch Next channel.

00:33:16.440 --> 00:33:18.910
The last thing my
app does is actually

00:33:18.910 --> 00:33:21.550
listen to the Added
to Watch Next.

00:33:21.550 --> 00:33:24.820
As you remember in the demo,
we long press on the program,

00:33:24.820 --> 00:33:28.630
click the Add to Watch Next, and
it was added to the Watch Next.

00:33:28.630 --> 00:33:32.170
What happened is that the system
actually takes the program

00:33:32.170 --> 00:33:34.810
from the apps channel
and copied it over

00:33:34.810 --> 00:33:36.250
to the Watch Next channel.

00:33:36.250 --> 00:33:40.090
We do that so that the visual
effects will be immediate.

00:33:40.090 --> 00:33:43.960
But what we also do is we send
an intent to my app to tell it,

00:33:43.960 --> 00:33:46.450
this program was copied and
added to the Watch Next,

00:33:46.450 --> 00:33:48.850
and what I did in
my app is, again,

00:33:48.850 --> 00:33:51.310
putting a receiver to
listen to these intents.

00:33:51.310 --> 00:33:53.680
And thee next thing
I do is start a job

00:33:53.680 --> 00:33:56.360
and I save this information
inside my own database.

00:33:56.360 --> 00:33:59.410
So when the firmware's updated,
maybe the number views change,

00:33:59.410 --> 00:34:02.392
I get a refresh of the
image, I can actually also

00:34:02.392 --> 00:34:03.850
update it in the
Watch Next channel

00:34:03.850 --> 00:34:05.099
so that content will be fresh.

00:34:10.469 --> 00:34:11.530
OK, so let's recap.

00:34:15.150 --> 00:34:17.650
What should I add under
the TV [INAUDIBLE]?

00:34:17.650 --> 00:34:20.280
So first of all, it needs to add
channel right after install--

00:34:20.280 --> 00:34:22.250
at least one.

00:34:22.250 --> 00:34:25.230
Keep the channels up to date,
refreshed, engage the user.

00:34:29.270 --> 00:34:33.770
Then I can suggest more
channels inside the app.

00:34:33.770 --> 00:34:35.679
Use the Watch Next
channel to engage the user

00:34:35.679 --> 00:34:38.590
to continue watching
the content.

00:34:38.590 --> 00:34:42.010
And listen and react
user interactions.

00:34:42.010 --> 00:34:46.422
And of course, do not
remove your first channel.

00:34:46.422 --> 00:34:47.880
Thank you for coming
and listening.

